<dl id="n54142b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54142b">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54142b"> 142(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> irascible plants pepper <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54142b"><li>FW 279. </li><li><a href="../../flex/le/lexle.htm#n54142b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/le/l39le.htm#n54142b">1939</a>f1 <a href="../../flex/le/lexle.htm#f101">&nbsp;fn101</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54142b">MS BL 47478-339</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:318 <a name="lad13" href="../../ff/fdra/lda.htm#led5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/le/led5.htm#n54142b">Draft: II.2&sect;6.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">A Nias, &laquo;un palmier &agrave; vin plant&eacute; par une femme donne plus de s&egrave;ve que s&apos;il l&apos;a &eacute;t&eacute; par un homme. Que la personne qui plante ait une influence sur la prosp&eacute;rit&eacute; du v&eacute;g&eacute;tal ressort aussi de ce fait que l&apos;insulaire de Nias ne plante son riz qu&apos;&agrave; un moment o&ugrave; il est enti&egrave;rement rassasi&eacute;, parce qu&apos;en cas contraire, croit-il, les &eacute;pis resteraient vides&hellip; Les Bataks ont une croyance semblable. Ils font semer <mark>leur poivre par des personnes particuli&egrave;rement violentes et col&eacute;reuses</mark>, afin que leur poivre devienne aussi br&ucirc;lant et mordant&raquo;. <br><font color="green">[In Nias, "a wine palm planted by a woman gives more sap than it was by a man. That the person who plants has an influence on the prosperity of the plant also emerges from this fact that the islander of Nias does not plant his rice until it is completely full, because otherwise, he believes, the ears of corn would remain empty &hellip; The Bataks have a similar belief. They sow their pepper by particularly violent and angry people, so that their pepper becomes as hot and biting".]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 254</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
